'''Frederick Joseph McEvoy''' (12 February 1907 – 7 November 1951) was an Australian born British multi-discipline sportsman and socialite.  He had most sporting success as a [[bobsleigh|bobsledder]] in the late 1930s, winning several medals including three golds at the [[FIBT World Championships]].  He married several wealthy heiresses and was a close friend of [[Errol Flynn]].  He usually shortened his name to Freddie McEvoy and was nicknamed "Suicide Freddie".

==Sporting achievements==

===Bobsleigh===
McEvoy was the [[List of flag bearers for Great Britain at the Olympics|British flag bearer]] at the [[1936 Winter Olympics]] in [[Garmisch-Partenkirchen]], Germany.<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/countries/GBR Great Britain] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100628000000/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/countries/GBR|date=28 June 2010}}. Olympics at Sport-Reference.com Sports Reference LLC; accessed 26 October 2011.</ref> 

He was part of the four-man bobsleigh team alongside [[James Cardno]], Gary Dugdale, and [[Charles Green (bobsleigh)|Charles Green]] who won the bronze medal in the four-man event.<ref>[http://www.databaseolympics.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=MCEVOFRE01 Frederick McEvoy] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070216162356/http://www.databaseolympics.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=MCEVOFRE01 |date=16 February 2007 }}. databaseOlympics.com. ''databaseSports.com''. Accessed 26 October 2011.</ref><ref>[http://sports123.com/bob/mo-4.html Olympic Games – Men: 4-Man]. ''Sports 123''. Accessed 26 October 2011.</ref> He also finished fourth in the two-man event with Cardno.<ref name="SR">[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/mc/freddie-mcevoy-1.html Freddie McEvoy Biography and Olympic Results] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120131081555/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/mc/freddie-mcevoy-1.html|date=31 January 2012}}. Sports-Reference.com. Sports Reference LLC; accessed 26 October 2011.</ref><ref>Krastev, Todor. [http://www.todor66.com/olim/1936w/Bobsleigh_Doubles.html Bobsleigh Doubles Olympic Games 1936 Garmish-Partenkirchen (GER); accessed 26 October 2011.</ref>

At the [[FIBT World Championships 1937|FIBT World Championships in 1937]] he realised greater success in the sport. Partnering [[Byran Black]] for the two-man at [[Cortina d'Ampezzo]], Italy he achieved his first gold medal.  He teamed up with Black, Olympic team-mate Charles Green, and [[David Looker]] in the four-man, again winning the gold medal.<ref name="sports123-4">[http://sports123.com/bob/mw-4.html World Championships – Men: 4-Man] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071211002351/http://sports123.com/bob/mw-4.html|date=11 December 2007}}. ''Sports 123''; accessed 26 October 2011.</ref><ref name="sports123-2">[http://sports123.com/bob/mw-2.html World Championships – Men: 2-Man] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929091333/http://sports123.com/bob/mw-2.html|date=29 September 2007}}. ''Sports 123''; accessed 26 October 2011.</ref>

At the [[FIBT World Championships 1938|same event in 1938]] three of the four-man riders returned to defend their title.  [[Chris MacKintosh]] replaced Byran Black and the team once again won the gold medal.  In the two-man race Charles Green partnered McEvoy and the pair won the silver medal.  Both men partnered again [[FIBT World Championships 1939|the following year]] and, alongside two new team-mates, won silver in the four-man event at Cortina d'Ampezzo.<ref name="sports123-4" /><ref name="sports123-2"/>

===Motor racing===
McEvoy came sixth in the 1936 [[Vanderbilt Cup]], racing a [[Maserati]] along the 300-mile course "considered by European road veterans to be probably the most severe test for man and car in the world".<ref>[http://www.sportscars.tv/Newfiles/vanderbilt36-7.html George Vanderbilt Cup Races 1936-7]. SportsCars.tv. Accessed 26 October 2011.</ref><ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article34956575?searchTerm=fred%20mcevoy&searchLimits= Motor Car Racing, American Contest, The Vanderbilt Cup]. ''[[Western Argus]]''. 20 October 1936. Accessed 26 October 2011.</ref> That same year he entered eight European races, usually driving a [[Maserati 6CM]],<ref>[http://www.racing-database.com/newdriv1.asp?Driver=Frederick%20McEvoy OVERALL RESULTS – Frederick McEvoy]. ''Racing Database''. Accessed 26 October 2011.</ref> with his best result of fourth place at both the XII Picardie on 21 June and the XII Coppa Acerbo on 15 August.<ref>[http://www.kolumbus.fi/leif.snellman/gp363.htm#18 1936 Part 3 XII GP DE PICARDIE]. Golden Era of Grand Prix Racing. Accessed 26 October 2011.</ref><ref>[http://www.kolumbus.fi/leif.snellman/gp365.htm#27 1936 Part 5 XII° COPPA ACERBO]. Golden Era of Grand Prix Racing. Accessed 26 October 2011.</ref>

==Other activities==
In 1943, McEvoy lived in Hollywood and was able to make uncredited appearances in two films.  The first was in ''[[Thank Your Lucky Stars (1943 film)|Thank Your Lucky Stars]]'' a scene starring good friend [[Errol Flynn]] in his only musical number.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0036422/fullcredits#cast Thank Your Lucky Stars (1943) – Full cast and crew]. [[Internet Movie Database]]. Accessed 26 October 2011.</ref> McEvoy's only other appearance was in ''[[The Desert Song (1943 film)|The Desert Song]]'', directed by [[Robert Florey]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0036755/fullcredits#cast The Desert Song (1943) – Full cast and crew]. [[Internet Movie Database]]. Accessed 26 October 2011.</ref>

There have been claims that McEvoy was an [[antisemitism|antisemite]] who covertly worked for the [[Third Reich]].<ref>Higham, Charles. [http://www.newstatesman.com/200004170041 The Missing Errol Flynn File]. ''[[New Statesman]]''. 17 April 2000. Accessed 26 October 2011.</ref> The FBI, who had him under surveillance along with several of his friends and associates, described him as "an international [[pimp]] who is interested in his own well-being and probably not engaged in activities detrimental to the interests of the country."<ref>McNulty, Thomas. [https://books.google.com/books?id=SMb1DpW1_YgC&pg=PA168&dq=freddy+mcevoy&hl=en&ei=Lx6oTpv1N4XVsgbsn_XRDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=mcevoy&f=false Errol Flynn: the life and career]. ''McFarland''. 2004. p.168.</ref>

Throughout 1944, McEvoy was believed to have smuggled guns, valuable jewellery, and alcohol from [[Mexico City]] to [[Beverly Hills]].<ref name="SR" />

McEvoy is said to have sold the shirt off his back for $2000 to an Argentine millionaire, "launch[ing] the fashion of flowered shirts for men".<ref name="TIME">[http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,857036,00.html MOROCCO: Death of a Playboy]. ''[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]''. 19 November 1951 (23 June 2011 excerpt). Accessed 26 October 2011.</ref>

==Personal life==
McEvoy was born in [[St Kilda, Victoria|St Kilda]], Victoria, Australia on 12 February 1907,<ref name="SR" /> the son of [[New Zealand]]-born Violet Healy and [[Melbourne]] native Frederick Aloysius McEvoy.<ref name="marrcert">{{cite web| title= Frederick James Mc Evoy and Irene Margaret Wrightsman| date= 11 February 1943| work=California, County Marriages, 1850–1952 | publisher= [[FamilySearch]]  |url= https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.1.1/K82P-G6W | accessdate= 23 June 2013}}</ref> The family moved to England early in his life.  McEvoy was given the nickname of "Suicide Freddie" because of his love of danger both in life and in sport.<ref name="TIME" /><ref>Gordon, Harry. [https://books.google.com/books?id=EMGFs3Vmk9cC&pg=PA271&lpg=PA271&dq=%22suicide+freddie%22+mcevoy&source=bl&ots=bes39_eu9d&sig=3Mrsc-sSTmNfB3_MZ10S_FakmVo&hl=en&ei=lYmoTtn2Ic2n8gObsbSnDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=%22suicide%20freddie%22%20mcevoy&f=false The time of our lives: inside the Sydney Olympics : Australia and the Olympic Games 1994–2002]. ''Univ. of Queensland Press''. 2003. p.271. Accessed 26 October 2011.</ref><ref name="PM">[http://www.pilotos-muertos.com/2011/McEvoy%20Freddie.html FREDDIE McEVOY – NO ERA UN SÍMBOLO (in Spanish)] (Freddie McEvoy – was not a symbol). www.pilotos-muertos.com. Accessed 26 October 2011.</ref> He was a rival of fellow racing driver and [[playboy (lifestyle)|playboy]] [[Porfirio Rubirosa]].<ref name="PM" />

===Marriage and relationships===
McEvoy was described by newspapers as an "internationally known Australian playboy" and a "popular, handsome, heiress hunter".<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article26595076/1766866?zoomLevel=3 Freddy McEvoy was playboy]. ''[[The Argus (Australia)|The Argus]]''. 7 March 1954. Accessed 26 October 2011.</ref><ref name="TCM">[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article50284868?searchTerm=fred%20mcevoy&searchLimits= Woolworth Heiress May Marry Austn.]. ''[[The Courier-Mail]]''. 13 April 1946. Accessed 26 October 2011.</ref> McEvoy considered himself, along with Rubirosa, the "Playboy of the Western World" and was rumoured to be very well endowed which may have been part of the allure to his female conquests.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/86738770/J-Edgar-Hoover-and-Clyde-Tolson-Darwin-Porter |title= J. Edgar Hoover & Clyde Tolson: Investigating the Sexual Secrets of America's Most Famous Men and Women | publisher= scribd.com| accessdate= 2 September 2012}}</ref>

McEvoy was married several times, taking his first wife in 1940.  [[Beatrice Cartwright]], a member of [[Charles Pratt|Pratt family]] and heir to a fortune from [[Standard Oil]], was twice his age and had lived with McEvoy for several years before their marriage.<ref name="SR" /> The union did not last, and in 1942 Cartwright accused McEvoy of being unfaithful with "three well-known society women".<ref name="Advertiser1942">[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article48888810?searchTerm=fred%20mcevoy&searchLimits= Flynn's Host Sued For Divorce]. ''[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]''. 28 October 1942. Accessed 26 October 2011.</ref> The divorce was granted on the grounds of misconduct.  McEvoy was not present for the decision as he was embroiled in a [[statutory rape]] case that had been opened against close friend Errol Flynn.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article56132052?searchTerm=fred%20mcevoy&searchLimits= Oil Heiress Granted Divorce]. ''[[The Morning Bulletin]]''. 30 October 1942. Accessed 26 October 2011.</ref> 17-year-old Betty Hansen had accused Flynn of committing the offence during a party at McEvoy's [[Bel Air, Los Angeles|Bel Air]] home, but McEvoy continued to publicly defend Flynn.<ref name="Advertiser1942" />

In February 1943,<ref name="marrcert"/> McEvoy married Irene Margaret Wrightsman, the daughter of [[Charles Bierer Wrightsman|Charles B. Wrightsman]],<ref name="marrcert"/> the president of [[Standard Oil]] of Kansas.  Wrightsman was 18 at the time of their wedding, nearly half his age.  Wrightsman was disinherited by her father after she eloped and the marriage lasted just two years.<ref name="SR" /><ref name="TCM" />

In 1945 he met [[Barbara Hutton]],<ref name="SR" /> another wealthy heiress who had just divorced third husband [[Cary Grant]].  Hutton was warned to stay away from McEvoy by friends and relatives and they assumed that the pair would marry as soon as he "legally divorces penniless Irene".<ref name="TCM" /> The couple were never wed, though Hutton bought a chalet at a ski resort in [[Franconia, New Hampshire]] and they lived together for a time.  Hutton married again in 1947 and she remained friends with McEvoy who went on to marry [[Claude Stephanie Filatre]], a French fashion model, in 1949.<ref name="SR" />

Errol Flynn married [[Patrice Wymore]] at a ceremony in [[Monte Carlo]] in 1950 with McEvoy as his best man and Filatre as the matron of honour.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18173687?searchTerm=fred%20mcevoy&searchLimits= Flynn Weds Starlet In Monte Carlo]. ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]''. 24 October 1950. Accessed 26 October 2011.</ref> At the time McEvoy was said to have been living in [[Cannes]] aboard his [[schooner]] ''Black Joke''.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18177643?searchTerm=fred%20mcevoy&searchLimits= Sydney Man To Be Best Man For Errol Flynn]. ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]''. 20 October 1950. Accessed 26 October 2011.</ref>

==Death==
McEvoy, his wife, and several others were sailing from [[Tangier]] to the [[Bahamas]] on his 104-ton schooner,<ref name="TIME" /> ''Kangaroo'', on 7 November 1951.  Just off the coast of [[Morocco]] a storm wrecked the ship and McEvoy swam to shore to look for help, leaving Claude Stephanie afloat on the mast.  He was unable to find any assistance and returned to his wife.  The pair tried to swim back to land but the waves were too strong.  Their bodies and those of four others were discovered the following day.<ref name="SR" /> One of the three survivors gave the name of Walter Praxmarer but was identified as Manfred Lenther, an Austrian man charged with murdering a woman in Berlin in 1945.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18239265?searchTerm=fred%20mcevoy&searchLimits= Strange Twist To Shipwreck Tragedy]. ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]''. 14 November 1951. Accessed 26 October 2011.</ref>

